 1434","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","Gorran, Cornwall, England":"Gorran, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Fentogollon, St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Hendower was born in 1400, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thomas de Hendower. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Sir William Tregarthen. She died in 1450, at the age of 50, and was buried in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1390–1445":"1390–1445","1427–1465":"1427–1465","1429–1508":"1429–1508","1434–Female":"1434–Surnud","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","8 September 1429":"8. september 1429","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","about 1434":"umbes 1434","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","Gorran, Cornwall, England":"Gorran, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Fentogollon, St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1390–1445":"1390–1445","1427–1465":"1427–1465","1429–1508":"1429–1508","1434–Female":"1434–Kuollut","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1390":"13